Search across my Gmail, Slack, Jira, Calendar, meeting notes, and relevant documents for the last 3-4 months. Act as my Chief of Staff and help me prepare a strong, honest, and strategically framed quarterly self-review.

Do this in two passes, not one.

PASS 1 — THEME DISCOVERY (do this first, then stop and wait for my input):
Search all sources and identify the major workstreams, relationships, decisions, and initiatives I was involved in. Then propose 3-5 themes that could define my quarter. For each theme, show me 2-3 pieces of supporting evidence from the data, tagged with SOURCE ATTRIBUTION format.

Also provide:
• A shortlist of weak evidence items, things I should avoid overstating
• Any areas where you need my input because data seems insufficient

Do NOT write the full review yet. Present the themes and wait for me to confirm, correct, add, or reprioritize. I will know things the data doesn't show, especially about strategic positioning, influence, trust-building, and cultural shifts.

PASS 2 — FULL REVIEW (only after I confirm themes):
Once confirmed, write the full review covering:

PRIORITIES — What were my main priorities, and to what extent were they met? Nominate 5 based on confirmed themes, recommend top 3 to lead with. For each: what was it, what I concretely did, what resulted, and whether it was fully met, partially met, or in progress. Distinguish outcomes from activity.

WHAT WORKED & WHAT TO IMPROVE — Assess execution strengths AND development areas. Be honest, specific, and growth-oriented. If I did something well, name it. If something needs work, frame it constructively with a plan to improve. Use my voice, direct and reflective.

NEXT QUARTER PRIORITIES — 3-5 suggestions with "success looks like" criteria. Require me to confirm and sharpen before finalizing.

Key framing instructions:
• My most important wins may be positional, relational, or cultural, not just shipped deliverables. A change in how leadership perceives my team is a legitimate outcome.
• Separate what I personally drove from what my team delivered under my direction. Both are valid but they're different claims.
• Don't flatten leadership work (advocacy, escalation, enablement, trust-building) into "activity." If it changed an outcome or shifted how people operate, it's a win.
• Still apply skepticism: don't overcredit routine participation or maintenance work.
• When something is genuinely in progress, frame it honestly as foundational work.

Output Structure:
A. Quarter at a Glance — the 3-5 confirmed themes
B. Strongest Wins — credible, evidence-backed, not inflated
C. Overclaimed or Weak Evidence Items — things to avoid overstating
D. Review Draft Answers — polished drafts in my voice
E. Coaching Notes — how to make it sound more strategic and honest

Tone: Direct, honest, no filler. Write like a senior professional who is self-aware and strategically minded. Give me the strongest version of the truth, not a flattering summary and not an unnecessarily harsh one either.
